        ## Execution context (settled - DO NOT re-litigate)

        - SD1: Process lifecycle states (not-installed, stopped, starting, ready, busy, degraded, failed, stopping) are namespaced under process contracts and never mapped to material statuses. - Preserves the locked material status vocabulary (missing|pending|resolved|stale|failed) and respects the North Star constraint that processes stay outside the V1 composition SDK.
- SD2: Output-format sidecar orchestration and process dashboard/UI are out of scope for M6a. - Plan explicitly narrows these out and explains they are bridges to later milestones, not contradictions. The runtime core still records sidecars/artifacts; full orchestration belongs to a future stage.
- SD3: Process execution is trusted and local only; no sandbox, marketplace, remote execution, or arbitrary shell access. - Directly aligned with North Star immutable constraint: 'No sandbox, marketplace, headless renderer, WebGPU, arbitrary material graphs, shader stacks, FBO chains, or generic texture routing in this epic.'

        ## Plan execution order rationale

        1. Land lifecycle and transport primitives first because all higher-level runtime work depends on their contracts.
2. Add `ProcessManager` and payload limits before changing adapters or command services, so host wiring has a real backend.
3. Bridge the process adapter and family assembly only after statuses can be projected from a manager.
4. Add blocker/diagnostic vocabulary before result attachment tests, so failures carry process correlation.
5. Implement `process.result.attach` before live-source integration, because both need stable process provenance and diagnostics.
6. Build the fixture after the manager contract stabilizes, then use it to replace fake-transport confidence with stdio integration confidence.

